My theoretical analysis draws from two sites of communal agency, particularly women’s: (Saba Mahmood’s study of) the women’s mosque movement as part of the larger Islamic Revival in contemporary Egypt, and Hồ Xuân Hương tradition of folk poetry contesting Confucian patriarchy in eighteenth-century Việt Nam. Not only do these two global sites differ historically and culturally, but they also reveal critically different forms of agency: one can be conceived as a “politics of piety” (as represented in Mahmood’s book
12
), whereas the other can be aptly called just the opposite, a politics of impiety. And yet, both sites offer a glimpse into multiple ways of being and acting in the world, challenging the overwhelming prevalence of a freedom-centered approach in political theory and international relations.

